 (a) To estimate the Doppler width $\Delta \nu_D / \nu$, we can use the formula:
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta \nu_D}{\nu} = \sqrt{\frac{8kT}{mc^2}}
\end{equation}
where $k$ is Boltzmann's constant, $m$ is the mass of the atom, $c$ is the speed of light, and $T$ is the temperature. Plugging in the given values, we get:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\Delta \nu_D}{\nu} &= \sqrt{\frac{8 \cdot 1.4 \times 10^{-23}}{4.2 \times 10^{-27} \cdot c^2}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{1.12 \times 10^{5}}{c^2}} \\
&\approx \boxed{6.9 \times 10^{-5}}
\end{align*}

(b) To estimate the pressure-broadened width of the line $\Delta \nu_p / \nu$, we need to know the cross-section for A*-A collisions. Let's assume that this cross-section is on the order of $10^{-19}$ m², which is typical for atomic collisions. We can then use the following formula to estimate the pressure broadening:
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta \nu_p}{\nu} = n \sigma v
\end{equation}
where $n$ is the number density of the gas, $\sigma$ is the cross-section, and $v$ is the average velocity of the atoms. First, let's find the number density using the ideal gas law:
\begin{align*}
n &= \frac{N}{V} \\
&= \frac{P}{RT} \\
&= \frac{100 \text{ Torr}}{\left(\frac{8.314 \text{ J/(mol K)}}{1 \text{ mol}}\right)(300 \text{ K})} \\
&\approx 4.0 \times 10^{25} \text{ m}^{-3}
\end{align*}
Next, let's find the average velocity of the atoms using the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution:
\begin{align*}
v_{\text{avg}} &= \sqrt{\frac{8kT}{\pi m}} \\
&= \sqrt{\frac{8 \cdot 1.4 \times 10^{-23}}{4.2 \times 10^{-27} \pi}} \\
&\approx 460 \text{ m/s}
\end{align*}
Now we can plug these values into our formula for pressure broadening:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\Delta \nu_p}{\nu} &= n \sigma v \\
&= (4.0 \times 10^{25})(10^{-19})(460) \\
&\approx \boxed{1.8 \times 10^{-2}}
\end{align*}
